// mentl_oracle.nx — the continuous oracle as IC + one cached value
//
// Mentl IS speculative inference. The oracle uses inference's primitives
// (graph_bind via trail-rollback) to explore alternate realities at every
// position with active dependents. She is not a peer to inference; she
// is inference run forward with hypothetical bindings rolled back, the
// survivors recorded as candidates.
//
// The oracle's exploration is Pure over (env + handler_chain + intent),
// matching IC's existing Pure over (ast + imports + handler_chain +
// intent). Per "Incremental Compilation Plus One Cached Value": IC's
// Cache handler stores (env, oracle_queue) per module instead of just
// env. Same invalidation discipline; same Pure-enables-memoization
// principle; the oracle's continuous-subscription substrate falls out
// of IC for free.
//
// Project queue = sorted merge of per-module cached queues. Surfaces
// query via OracleQuery; surface query is itself memoizable (Pure over
// the set of cache hashes).
//
// The build IS a `<~` feedback loop: source change → IC invalidates
// affected modules → re-infer + re-explore → project queue refreshes →
// highest-priority next-step surfaces → user acts → loop. Silence ONLY
// when the project queue is empty — the gradient's top, the proven-
// complete state.
//
// Authority:
// - SUBSTRATE.md §"Incremental Compilation: Purity Enables Caching" (L480-505)
// - SUBSTRATE.md §"Inference IS the Light" (L50-66)
// - SUBSTRATE.md §"The Duty of Inference is Reification" (L77-90)
// - SUBSTRATE.md §"The Hole Is the Gradient's Absence Marker" (commit 7505ade)
// - SUBSTRATE.md §"Feedback Is Inka's Genuine Novelty" (L1761-1796)
// - CLAUDE.md Mentl's anchor + eight interrogations
// - src/mentl.nx:155-175 (existing speculative loop — extends here)
// - src/graph.nx graph_handler (trail substrate already in place)
// - src/cache.nx Cache handler (extends here to store oracle_queue)

import types
import mentl
import graph

// ─── QueueItem — one proven candidate in the oracle's queue ──────────

/// QueueItem — one proven candidate Mentl could surface. Each carries
/// the position the candidate applies to, the candidate itself (an
/// Annotation per src/mentl.nx), the capability it would unlock, an
/// OraclePriority for ranking, the proof-chain Reason that justified
/// inclusion, and the module that owns it. Surfaces query the queue
/// and render the highest-priority item visible at the cursor or
/// project-wide.
///
/// Primitives: #2 (Propose — the candidate); #6 (Verify — the proof);
/// #7 (Teach — the gradient direction); #8 (Reason — the chain).

type QueueItem
  = QueueItem({
      position:    Int,              // graph Handle where item applies
      candidate:   Annotation,       // what to add (per src/mentl.nx Annotation)
      capability:  Capability,       // what it unlocks (per src/mentl.nx Capability)
      impact:      OraclePriority,
      reason:      Reason,
      module_path: String
    })

/// OraclePriority — ranking dimension. The priority function composes
/// tier (compile-blocking first) + intent_weight (per declared user
/// Intent — `IntRealTime` weights `!Alloc` violations heavier) +
/// surface_area (count of dependent positions affected) + locality_bias
/// (distance from cursor in bytes; 0 = exact). Total order via
/// priority_lt. The composition discipline is "compile-blocking
/// always wins; among same-tier items, intent-weight wins; among
/// same-intent items, surface-area wins; among same-surface items,
/// locality wins."

type OraclePriority
  = OraclePriority({
      tier:          PriorityTier,
      intent_weight: Int,            // 0-100; higher = more weighted
      surface_area:  Int,            // count of dependent positions
      locality_bias: Int             // distance bytes from cursor; 0 = exact
    })

/// PriorityTier — five tiers in compile-impact order. TBlocking is the
/// fix-this-or-nothing-compiles tier (always wins). TViolation is
/// declared-row contradicted (E_PurityViolated, E_OwnershipViolation,
/// E_RowSubsumptionFailed). TPending is V_Pending refinement obligation
/// not yet discharged. TUnlock is gradient capability available
/// (`with !Alloc`, `with Pure`, refinement narrowing). TStyle is
/// topology nudge (use `|>` instead of nested calls). H6 exhaustive.

type PriorityTier
  = TBlocking
  | TViolation
  | TPending
  | TUnlock
  | TStyle

/// OracleQueue — per-module sorted list of QueueItems. Ranked by
/// descending priority. Cached alongside the module's env via the
/// extended IC Cache handler; invalidates together with env on any
/// cache miss. Pure over (env + handler_chain + intent).

type OracleQueue
  = OracleQueue(List)               // List<QueueItem>, sorted by priority_gt

// ─── Mutate effect extension — graph_mutated event ───────────────────

/// graph_mutated is performed by graph_handler at the OUTERMOST commit
/// boundary — speculative writes (between graph_push_checkpoint and
/// graph_rollback) DO NOT emit; they reach this only if committed.
/// Otherwise Mentl would subscribe to her own speculations and
/// recursively explore forever.
///
/// Subscribers (cached_check_with_oracle) catch this event and walk
/// the dependency graph to invalidate affected per-module cache entries
/// per the Q-2 (B) scope rule (transitive dependents via Reason chain).
///
/// The Mutate effect at types.nx:641 was a marker effect with no ops;
/// this extends it. Composition lands in types.nx in the same commit
/// as this substrate.

// (The op declaration lives in types.nx; this file documents intent.)

// ─── OracleQuery effect — surfaces read oracle state ─────────────────

/// OracleQuery — read-only queries from surfaces. The `!Mutate`
/// constraint on subscriber rows proves no surface can corrupt the
/// oracle. All ops are Pure-over-cached-state — surfaces query without
/// triggering re-exploration; the oracle re-explores only when
/// graph_mutated fires (which IC governs).
///
/// Five surfaces today subscribe through these ops:
/// - `voice_queue_walk` (cursor-time MV) — query_project_queue +
///   cursor_relevant
/// - `inka doc` (F.1 batch) — query_module_queue per decl
/// - LSP hover — query_at_position(cursor_handle)
/// - `inka teach` CLI — query_at_position OR query_project_queue
/// - Web playground — same as LSP, push via WebSocket on queue change

effect OracleQuery {
  query_at_position(Int)            -> List   @resume=OneShot   // List<QueueItem> at this Handle
  query_project_queue()             -> List   @resume=OneShot   // List<QueueItem> merged from all modules
  query_module_queue(String)        -> List   @resume=OneShot   // List<QueueItem> for one module
  cursor_relevant(Int, Int)         -> List   @resume=OneShot   // (cursor_handle, max_distance_bytes); locality-filtered
}

// ─── cached_check_with_oracle — IC Cache shape extension ─────────────

/// cached_check_with_oracle — extends IC's Cache handler shape to store
/// (env, oracle_queue) per module instead of just env. Same hash key
/// (ast + imports + handler_chain + intent); same invalidation
/// discipline; one extra cached value.
///
/// Per the IC + oracle composition: oracle is Pure over (env +
/// handler_chain + intent), matching IC's Pure over (ast + imports +
/// handler_chain + intent). Both invalidate together on any input
/// change — there is no separate oracle cache layer; one cache, two
/// values.
///
/// graph_mutated arm is the IC trigger: when inference commits writes
/// at the outermost level, walk the dependency graph and invalidate
/// affected per-module entries.

handler cached_check_with_oracle
  with cache = empty_cache() {

  /// infer arm — cache lookup; on miss, run check + oracle, store both.
  /// Returns (env, oracle_queue) so downstream handlers (project queue
  /// merger, voice_queue_walk) read both from the same call.
  infer(ast) => {
    let key = oracle_cache_key(ast)
    match cache_lookup(cache, key) {
      Some(entry)   => {
        let CachedEntry(env, queue) = entry
        resume((env, queue))
      },
      None          => {
        let env       = run_check(ast)
        let queue     = run_oracle(env, module_path_of(ast))
        let new_cache = cache_store(cache, key, CachedEntry(env, queue))
        resume((env, queue))
          with cache = new_cache
      }
    }
  },

  /// graph_mutated arm — IC's invalidation trigger. Walks the
  /// dependency graph (Q-2 (B) scope) — every module whose cached env
  /// transitively depends on the mutated handle gets invalidated. Per-
  /// module queue contributions invalidate together with env.
  graph_mutated(epoch, mutation) => {
    let affected_modules = invalidation_walk(cache, mutation)
    let new_cache        = cache_invalidate_set(cache, affected_modules)
    resume()
      with cache = new_cache
  }
}

// ─── project_queue_merger — derived merge of per-module queues ───────

/// project_queue_merger — the project-wide priority queue is a sorted
/// merge of per-module cached queues. Cheap to assemble (per-module
/// queues are already sorted; merge is O(N log M) for N total items
/// across M modules). Itself memoizable: if no module's cache hash
/// changed, the merged queue is unchanged. Pure over the set of cache
/// hashes.
///
/// query_project_queue checks the cache-hash-set; if unchanged, returns
/// last_merge_queue; if changed, re-merges and updates state.

handler project_queue_merger
  with last_merge_hash = 0,
       merged_queue    = OracleQueue([]) {

  /// query_project_queue — returns the merged project-wide queue.
  /// Memoized: cache-hash-set unchanged → return last merge.
  query_project_queue() => {
    let current_hash = perform compute_cache_hash_set()
    if current_hash == last_merge_hash {
      let OracleQueue(items) = merged_queue
      resume(items)
    } else {
      let queues  = perform collect_module_queues()
      let merged  = merge_priority_queues(queues)
      let OracleQueue(items) = merged
      resume(items)
        with last_merge_hash = current_hash,
             merged_queue    = merged
    }
  },

  /// query_at_position — items in the queue that apply at this Handle.
  /// Filters the project queue; cheap because items carry their position.
  query_at_position(handle) => {
    let queue = perform query_project_queue()
    resume(filter_at_position(queue, handle))
  },

  /// query_module_queue — items for one module (cache-direct read).
  query_module_queue(module_path) => {
    let entry = perform cache_get_module_entry(module_path)
    match entry {
      Some(CachedEntry(_, OracleQueue(items)))  => resume(items),
      None                                      => resume([])
    }
  },

  /// cursor_relevant — locality-filtered items. Surfaces use this when
  /// they want to bias toward the cursor's region (LSP hover, inline
  /// hints) but fall back to project-wide priority when cursor's
  /// region is silent. The fallback decision lives in the surface
  /// (voice_queue_walk), not here.
  cursor_relevant(cursor_handle, max_distance_bytes) => {
    let queue = perform query_project_queue()
    resume(filter_by_locality(queue, cursor_handle, max_distance_bytes))
  }
}

// ─── run_oracle — per-module exploration producing an OracleQueue ────

/// run_oracle — produces a per-module OracleQueue from a checked env.
/// Walks every position in the module that has dependents (Q-2 (B)
/// scope), runs speculative-inference candidate enumeration per the
/// existing src/mentl.nx try_each_annotation_loop pattern, ranks
/// survivors via priority_lt, returns the sorted queue.
///
/// Pure-equivalent over (env + handler_chain + intent) — performs only
/// Verify (refinement obligations) and uses graph_push_checkpoint /
/// graph_rollback (from `Speculate` row, an effect-row commitment that
/// the writes will be reverted). Same memoizability discipline as
/// inference.
///
/// Pre-B.2: candidate enumeration is OneShot per candidate (sequential).
/// Post-B.2: candidate enumeration parallelizes via MultiShot fork; same
/// substrate; just faster (the kernel claim "hundreds of universes per
/// second" lands at this point — speculative forks per position run
/// concurrently, survivors merge into the queue).

fn run_oracle(env, module_path) with Verify =
  let positions = collect_positions_with_dependents(env)
  let n         = len(positions)
  let buf       = make_list(n * 4)        // generous estimate; over-alloc fine
  let count     = explore_positions(positions, 0, n, env, module_path, buf, 0)
  OracleQueue(sort_by_priority(slice(buf, 0, count)))

/// explore_positions — fold over positions; per-position, enumerate
/// candidates and try each. Tail-recursive accumulator; flat-buffer-
/// plus-counter substrate (Ω.3 — list_extend_to + list_set + counter +
/// slice; the substrate idiom that avoids the appended-bracket-x
/// O(N²) loop pattern).

fn explore_positions(positions, i, n, env, module_path, buf, count) with Verify =
  if i >= n { count }
  else {
    let handle = list_index(positions, i)
    let candidates = enumerate_candidates_at(handle, env)
    let new_count  = try_each_candidate_to_queue(handle, candidates, env, module_path, buf, count)
    explore_positions(positions, i + 1, n, env, module_path, buf, new_count)
  }

/// try_each_candidate_to_queue — for each candidate at a position,
/// checkpoint → tentative apply → verify → rollback → on success,
/// append a QueueItem to the buffer with computed priority. Extends
/// src/mentl.nx try_each_annotation_loop to write to the queue
/// instead of returning a tuple list.

fn try_each_candidate_to_queue(handle, candidates, env, module_path, buf, count) with Verify =
  let n = len(candidates)
  try_each_candidate_loop(handle, candidates, 0, n, env, module_path, buf, count)

fn try_each_candidate_loop(handle, candidates, i, n, env, module_path, buf, count) with Verify =
  if i >= n { count }
  else {
    let cand    = list_index(candidates, i)
    let cp      = perform graph_push_checkpoint()
    let _       = apply_candidate_tentatively(handle, cand, env)
    let proven  = verify_after_apply(handle)
    let _       = perform graph_rollback(cp)
    if proven {
      let priority = compute_priority(handle, cand, env, module_path)
      let item     = QueueItem({
        position:    handle,
        candidate:   cand,
        capability:  unlock_capability(cand),
        impact:      priority,
        reason:      OracleVerified(handle, cand),
        module_path: module_path
      })
      let extended = list_extend_to(buf, count + 1)
      let written  = list_set(extended, count, item)
      try_each_candidate_loop(handle, candidates, i + 1, n, env, module_path, written, count + 1)
    }
    else {
      try_each_candidate_loop(handle, candidates, i + 1, n, env, module_path, buf, count)
    }
  }

// ─── silence_predicate (revised per Q-Morgan-B) ──────────────────────

/// silence_predicate — Mentl is silent ONLY when the project queue is
/// empty. The gradient's top: nothing more to add; everything proven.
/// Until then, Mentl always surfaces the highest-priority next step.
///
/// This REPLACES the per-Topic novelty check from D.1.c. Earlier
/// silence semantics were too coarse — silenced Mentl when she had
/// more to say project-wide. New semantics: silence ONLY when the
/// project is at the gradient's top.
///
/// The per-Topic / per-tentacle render-or-not decision moves to the
/// surface (voice_queue_walk — see queue_to_voicelines). What this
/// predicate gates is the STRONG silence: no more proven next-steps
/// anywhere in the project.

fn silence_predicate_oracle(situation) with OracleQuery =
  let queue = perform query_project_queue()
  match queue {
    []        => true,    // gradient at top — full silence
    [_ | _]   => false    // queue has items — Mentl surfaces something
  }

// ─── Priority function — total order over OraclePriority ─────────────

/// priority_lt — total order. Tier wins first; among same-tier,
/// intent_weight wins; among same-intent, surface_area wins; among
/// same-surface, locality wins (closer to cursor wins).

fn priority_lt(a, b) with Pure =
  let OraclePriority(pa) = a
  let OraclePriority(pb) = b
  if !tier_eq(pa.tier, pb.tier)                 { tier_lt(pa.tier, pb.tier) }
  else if pa.intent_weight != pb.intent_weight  { pa.intent_weight > pb.intent_weight }
  else if pa.surface_area != pb.surface_area    { pa.surface_area > pb.surface_area }
  else                                          { pa.locality_bias < pb.locality_bias }

/// priority_gt — descending order; just !priority_lt for non-equal.
fn priority_gt(a, b) with Pure =
  !priority_lt(a, b) && !priority_eq(a, b)

fn priority_eq(a, b) with Pure =
  let OraclePriority(pa) = a
  let OraclePriority(pb) = b
  tier_eq(pa.tier, pb.tier)
    && pa.intent_weight == pb.intent_weight
    && pa.surface_area  == pb.surface_area
    && pa.locality_bias == pb.locality_bias

/// tier_lt — total order over PriorityTier (TBlocking < TViolation <
/// TPending < TUnlock < TStyle). H6 exhaustive 5-arm match via tier_rank.

fn tier_lt(a, b) with Pure =
  tier_rank(a) < tier_rank(b)

fn tier_eq(a, b) with Pure =
  tier_rank(a) == tier_rank(b)

fn tier_rank(t) with Pure =
  match t {
    TBlocking   => 0,
    TViolation  => 1,
    TPending    => 2,
    TUnlock     => 3,
    TStyle      => 4
  }

// ─── Helper interfaces (bodies live in their primitive's home file) ──

/// oracle_cache_key — the cache key composing ast + imports +
/// handler_chain + intent. Body lives in src/cache.nx alongside
/// existing IC keys. Declared here for the contract.

fn oracle_cache_key(ast) with Memory =
  perform compute_oracle_cache_key(ast)

/// invalidation_walk — given a graph mutation, compute the set of
/// per-module cache keys that should be invalidated. Walks the
/// dependency graph IC already uses (per Q-2 (B) scope rule). Body
/// in src/cache.nx.

fn invalidation_walk(cache, mutation) with GraphRead =
  perform compute_invalidation_set(cache, mutation)

/// merge_priority_queues — sorted merge of List<OracleQueue>.
/// Body in lib/runtime/lists.nx (or this file extends if no good home).
/// O(N log M) where N = total items, M = module count.

fn merge_priority_queues(queues) with Memory =
  // Implemented by merge_sorted_lists with priority_gt as comparator.
  perform merge_lists_by(queues, priority_gt)

/// filter_at_position / filter_by_locality / collect_module_queues /
/// compute_cache_hash_set / cache_get_module_entry / module_owning /
/// module_path_of / collect_positions_with_dependents /
/// enumerate_candidates_at / apply_candidate_tentatively /
/// verify_after_apply / unlock_capability — all delegate to their
/// primitive's home file (src/cache.nx for cache ops; src/mentl.nx
/// for candidate enumeration; src/graph.nx for position/dependents
/// walks). Declared here as the contract; substrate in their home
/// files lands in subsequent commits.

// ─── Connection to the kernel ─────────────────────────────────────────

/// Primitive #1 (Graph + Env) — the oracle reads from the same graph
/// inference reads from; per-position state lives at the position's
/// Handle; oracle_queue is itself a graph-resident value (cached per-
/// module via IC).
///
/// Primitive #2 (Handlers + resume discipline) — oracle is structured
/// as handlers (cached_check_with_oracle, project_queue_merger);
/// candidate enumeration uses MultiShot resume discipline (post-B.2)
/// for parallel speculation. Pre-B.2 uses OneShot sequential per the
/// existing src/mentl.nx pattern; same substrate, just faster post-B.2.
///
/// Primitive #3 (Five verbs) — the build IS a `<~` feedback loop:
/// `compile ~> cached_check_with_oracle <~ user_action`. Per
/// INSIGHTS L1761 ("Feedback Is Inka's Genuine Novelty"), the cycle
/// is visible at the syntactic level.
///
/// Primitive #4 (Effect row algebra) — oracle handler performs
/// `Verify + GraphRead + Speculate`; surfaces declare `OracleQuery +
/// !Mutate` proving they can't corrupt oracle state.
///
/// Primitive #5 (Ownership) — base graph `ref` to oracle; speculative
/// fork writes `own` to the oracle (rolled back); cached oracle_queue
/// `own` to the cache; surfaces read via `ref`.
///
/// Primitive #6 (Refinement) — every QueueItem must satisfy
/// verify_after_apply to enter the queue (proven candidate); items
/// without proven verification never reach the surface.
///
/// Primitive #7 (Annotation gradient) — the oracle IS the gradient's
/// runtime substrate; QueueItem.candidate IS one gradient step;
/// surfaces show the highest-priority next step per the "ONE step per
/// turn" discipline (INSIGHTS L731-734); silence ONLY at gradient top.
///
/// Primitive #8 (HM inference + Reasons) — every QueueItem carries
/// its proof-chain Reason (OracleVerified); the Why Engine walks back
/// to "why did Mentl propose this?"
///
/// Mentl tentacle mapping:
/// - Query reads cached env state at the cursor's position
/// - Propose surfaces QueueItem candidates from the queue
/// - Topology proposes |> rewrites (TStyle tier)
/// - Unlock surfaces TUnlock-tier items at the cursor
/// - Trace surfaces TViolation-tier items
/// - Verify surfaces TPending-tier items
/// - Teach surfaces the highest-priority TUnlock + cursor-locality
/// - Why walks the QueueItem.reason chain on user request
///
/// One oracle, eight tentacle projections, one queue. Mentl's eight
/// tentacles are filtered views over the same priority queue.

// ─── What this substrate refuses ──────────────────────────────────────

/// - Separate continuous oracle process. The oracle IS IC + one cached
///   value; no daemon; no concurrent-runtime layer; IC is the scheduler.
/// - Per-Topic silence-gating. Earlier silence_predicate (D.1.c) is
///   superseded — the surface decides what to render based on cursor-
///   relevance + global fallback; silence is now the strong "gradient
///   top" signal only.
/// - Eager per-position re-exploration on every keystroke. The oracle
///   re-explores when IC says the relevant module needs re-inference;
///   IC's existing dependency graph IS the invalidation scope.
/// - Subscribing to Mentl's own speculative writes. graph_mutated fires
///   only at outermost commit boundaries; speculative writes between
///   checkpoint-rollback never reach subscribers (otherwise infinite
///   recursion).
/// - Surfaces mutating oracle state. OracleQuery is read-only; the
///   `!Mutate` row constraint on subscribers proves the substrate
///   discipline at compile time.
///
/// Inka solves Inka. The oracle is what falls out of IC + Pure-over-
/// broader-input + the existing speculative-inference loop. No new
/// substrate primitives; one extra cached value; one event boundary.
